1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,340
In this demo, we'll first take a look at how we can assess the impact of data cleaning.

2
00:00:04,340 --> 00:00:06,280
We've already covered ways to do this using

3
00:00:06,280 --> 00:00:09,340
visual inspection with methods like.head and.tail.

4
00:00:09,340 --> 00:00:11,200
But what about visualizations?

5
00:00:11,200 --> 00:00:14,490
While we briefly covered boxplots as a way to visualize outliers,

6
00:00:14,490 --> 00:00:16,350
let's look at heatmaps and histograms as

7
00:00:16,350 --> 00:00:19,600
two other visualizations that data sprinklers typically use.

8
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:22,000
Here I've loaded my PUMS dataset.

9
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,920
I'm trying to test if I handle the missing data correctly.

10
00:00:24,920 --> 00:00:29,260
First, we have a code block where we take care of a couple of cleaning operations,

11
00:00:29,260 --> 00:00:31,360
starting with making copy of the DataFrame,

12
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:35,200
dealing with a tidiness issue by defining the zeroth row as our header,

13
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:36,855
keeping our WRK, SEX,

14
00:00:36,855 --> 00:00:40,960
and SCOP variables and dealing with a data quality issue by

15
00:00:40,960 --> 00:00:46,595
replacing zero values in the word column with np.nan to deal with the completeness issue.

16
00:00:46,595 --> 00:00:48,860
Now that all of the cleaning code is complete,

17
00:00:48,860 --> 00:00:50,045
let's skip over to say,

18
00:00:50,045 --> 00:00:53,345
how do we visualize the missing values in our semi cleaned data?

19
00:00:53,345 --> 00:00:57,515
Take a look at this heatmap visualization that I generated using the Seaborne library,

20
00:00:57,515 --> 00:00:59,900
where we visualize the patterns of missing data

21
00:00:59,900 --> 00:01:02,330
for some variables from the PUMS dataset,

22
00:01:02,330 --> 00:01:04,835
including the occupational code variable,

23
00:01:04,835 --> 00:01:06,375
the SOCP variable,

24
00:01:06,375 --> 00:01:08,600
the gender, and whether or not an individual

25
00:01:08,600 --> 00:01:11,345
worked in the last week indicated by the WRK variable.

26
00:01:11,345 --> 00:01:13,085
Here, in order to create the heatmap,

27
00:01:13,085 --> 00:01:16,220
I'm using the.isna method and transposing

28
00:01:16,220 --> 00:01:19,955
this and then providing it as input to the Seaborne heatmap function,

29
00:01:19,955 --> 00:01:24,950
while also specifying the label for the missing data legend at the side.

30
00:01:24,950 --> 00:01:27,470
The white vertical bars in this heatmap are

31
00:01:27,470 --> 00:01:29,760
representing missing values for a particular variable.

32
00:01:29,760 --> 00:01:34,085
In this case we can actually see a number of missing values for the WRK column.

33
00:01:34,085 --> 00:01:37,220
I'm going to go ahead now and use the Drop NA function

34
00:01:37,220 --> 00:01:40,415
on this PUMS dataset to get rid of those NA values.

35
00:01:40,415 --> 00:01:42,035
Now if we re-run the heatmap,

36
00:01:42,035 --> 00:01:45,730
there's no white lines and the color indicates there isn't any missing data.

37
00:01:45,730 --> 00:01:50,630
Another way to visualize data is plotting a histogram of the distribution of data values.

38
00:01:50,630 --> 00:01:52,400
Let's go ahead and load another dataset,

39
00:01:52,400 --> 00:01:56,045
the OEWS wage data set and similarly do some cleaning.

40
00:01:56,045 --> 00:01:58,565
I'm making a copy of the DataFrame down here,

41
00:01:58,565 --> 00:02:01,850
replacing alphanumeric characters with NAs,

42
00:02:01,850 --> 00:02:05,210
filtering the DataFrame to only contain specific data variables

43
00:02:05,210 --> 00:02:09,185
and filtering to only contain values that are corresponding to California.

44
00:02:09,185 --> 00:02:11,760
Finally, I also drop NA values.

45
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:14,915
Here now what I'm going to do is plot the age mean or

46
00:02:14,915 --> 00:02:17,480
hourly mean numeric variable in my dataset

47
00:02:17,480 --> 00:02:21,230
indicating the hourly mean wage from my cleaned wage DataFrame.

48
00:02:21,230 --> 00:02:24,005
I'm using the simple plot.hist function for this,

49
00:02:24,005 --> 00:02:27,440
defining the number of bins for my histogram as 12 and

50
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:31,040
the transparency value for the plot to be 0.5 for aesthetic reasons.

51
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:34,225
The plot.hist function is from the Matplotlib library.

52
00:02:34,225 --> 00:02:35,960
Now, with this visualization,

53
00:02:35,960 --> 00:02:39,065
I can quickly grasp the range of values for this variable.

54
00:02:39,065 --> 00:02:43,685
For example, ranging from about $10-160 at quick glance.

55
00:02:43,685 --> 00:02:46,060
This seems to be the typical range of the data.

56
00:02:46,060 --> 00:02:48,620
I can also identify if there are any outliers or data

57
00:02:48,620 --> 00:02:51,905
points that seem anomalous in relation to the larger chunk of data.

58
00:02:51,905 --> 00:02:55,015
Like some of these data points here at the far right of the plot.

59
00:02:55,015 --> 00:02:59,960
This can help me with identifying potential validity issues as well and accuracy issues.

60
00:02:59,960 --> 00:03:02,780
How can we test data programmatically including whether

61
00:03:02,780 --> 00:03:05,665
we successfully dropped the NAs for both datasets?

62
00:03:05,665 --> 00:03:08,420
We can actually use Python assert statements to

63
00:03:08,420 --> 00:03:11,780
check if certain conditions we know should hold true for our datasets.

64
00:03:11,780 --> 00:03:13,535
Those are indeed true.

65
00:03:13,535 --> 00:03:17,440
For example, we can use it to check whether our column datatypes are accurate.

66
00:03:17,440 --> 00:03:19,865
In this case, let's say we've determined that we want

67
00:03:19,865 --> 00:03:24,400
all the variables to be at the object's data type in the PUMS dataset.

68
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:28,310
We can actually go ahead and do that and using the assert statement by accessing

69
00:03:28,310 --> 00:03:30,290
the datatype using the dtype method for each of

70
00:03:30,290 --> 00:03:32,630
the columns and asserting that they're all objects.

71
00:03:32,630 --> 00:03:34,820
Similarly for the OEWS dataset,

72
00:03:34,820 --> 00:03:37,925
we want to check if the datatype of each mean is a float.

73
00:03:37,925 --> 00:03:41,065
Because it's a numerical variable we can do the same thing here.

74
00:03:41,065 --> 00:03:43,580
We can also check if the number of NA values and

75
00:03:43,580 --> 00:03:45,800
our code is set to zero for both datasets.

76
00:03:45,800 --> 00:03:49,040
Here we use isnull.sum.sum in order to calculate the number

77
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:52,840
of NA values and check that it's zero for both datasets.

78
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:57,590
We can see that since these assert statements have successfully run and no issues there,

79
00:03:57,590 --> 00:03:59,390
everything is good and there really are

80
00:03:59,390 --> 00:04:03,265
no NA values in this dataset when we use this programmatic check.

81
00:04:03,265 --> 00:04:06,590
What happens if the cleaning code didn't work and the data didn't meet

82
00:04:06,590 --> 00:04:09,560
the condition we specified in the assert statements though?

83
00:04:09,560 --> 00:04:11,240
For example, let's say that I determined that

84
00:04:11,240 --> 00:04:16,670
the hourly mean wage values in the data should be smaller than or equal to 150.

85
00:04:16,670 --> 00:04:18,770
Because any value greater than 150,

86
00:04:18,770 --> 00:04:20,800
as an example, is an outlier to me.

87
00:04:20,800 --> 00:04:23,575
I use the assert statement to test this condition.

88
00:04:23,575 --> 00:04:26,990
You can see now that the assert statement is throwing us an error because we

89
00:04:26,990 --> 00:04:31,235
never removed these outliers that we identified earlier through the histogram.

90
00:04:31,235 --> 00:04:35,660
Assert statements are indeed useful when you need to modify earlier cleaning code to

91
00:04:35,660 --> 00:04:37,460
address new data problems and want to

92
00:04:37,460 --> 00:04:40,190
ensure that previously solved issues remain resolved.

93
00:04:40,190 --> 00:04:43,610
For example, if you want to verify that these NA values

94
00:04:43,610 --> 00:04:46,985
for the two datasets remain at zero as you're addressing other data issues,

95
00:04:46,985 --> 00:04:48,605
you can use assert statements.

96
00:04:48,605 --> 00:04:53,060
These single line statements allow you to confirm that your cleaning code is working as

97
00:04:53,060 --> 00:04:58,290
expected by re-running them whenever you make changes to your implementation.

